### 3.1. Add a new image via base64 (alternative method)
POST http://localhost:8000/api/image
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "My First Image",
  "imageData": "iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAYAAAAfFcSJAAAADUlEQVR42mNkYPhfDwAChwGA60e6kgAAAABJRU5ErkJggg=="
}

###

### 4. Delete an image by ID (with user ownership verification)
### 4.1. Delete image with correct user ID (should succeed)
DELETE http://localhost:8000/api/image/1?userId=1
Content-Type: application/json

###

### 4.2. Delete image with wrong user ID (should fail with 403 Forbidden)
DELETE http://localhost:8000/api/image/1?userId=2
Content-Type: application/json

###

### 4.3. Delete non-existent image (should fail with 404 Not Found)
DELETE http://localhost:8000/api/image/999?userId=1
Content-Type: application/json

###

### 5. Reset database (delete all images)
DELETE http://localhost:8000/api/image/reset-db
Content-Type: application/json

###

### Notes:
### - Application configured to run on port 8000
### - The imageData field must contain a valid base64 string of an image
### - To convert an image to base64, you can use online tools or code
### - Example base64 image (1x1 transparent pixel): iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAYAAAAfFcSJAAAADUlEQVR42mNkYPhfDwAChwGA60e6kgAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==
### - LIMIT: Maximum of 10 images per system
### 
### ACCESS CONTROL:
### - DELETE endpoint now requires userId parameter to verify ownership
### - Only the user who uploaded the image can delete it
### - Returns 403 Forbidden if user tries to delete another user's image
### - Returns 404 Not Found if image doesn't exist
### - Example: DELETE /api/image/1?userId=1 (where 1 is the image owner's ID)
